docs.text: instinct is the kind of movie that inexperienced moviegoers will undoubtedly label as " powerful " or " touching " .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: i have a name for it myself : " gross " .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: this is the sort of film where somebody stands up to a bully , the bully looks at the " rebel " threateningly , about to hurt him , and then everyone else whom the bully has heretofore controlled stands up too .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: how that scene is still present in so many movies today appalls me : aren't present day moviegoers beyond being " inspired " by something like that ?
docs.label: negative

docs.text: this is one example ( there are actually some more in instinct alone ) of filmmakers insulting the audience's intelligence .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: instinct's plot is brimming with potential : world-renowned anthropologist ethan powell ( anthony hopkins ) disappeared for two years whilst doing research in the jungles of africa .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: he was found and is coming back to the united states a convicted killer ; he murdered to african policemen who were allegedly trying to capture him .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: after committing a few more brutal acts of violence in the airport , the authorities stick him in a prison's " psychotics ward " .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: assigned to do an evaluation on powell is a bright ( or so we are told ) young psychiatrist theo caulder ( cuba gooding jr . ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: caulder starts out doing the evaluation merely for the purpose of furthering his career .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: of course ( and no mainstream filmmaker would ever have it any other way ) he starts really caring for powell and he becomes fixed on helping powell prove that he is not a psychotic and that he should not be in prison .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: and then there's the inevitable " heartless meanie " character , in the form of donald sutherland who plays caulder's mentor .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: he cares for caulder but does everything he can to discourage him from helping powell .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: let's get one thing straight : dr . theo caulder is the most blatantly incompetent psychiatrist i have ever seen , on screen or off .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: any good shrink will listen to what his patient has to say no matter the subject because any good shrink will learn a great deal about his patient that way .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: not good old theo .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: no , he asks purposefully pointed questions and when powell dares to venture to another subject caulder says " we need to talk about this right now . "
docs.label: negative

docs.text: this is a flaw only in the sense that it detracts from instinct's already dubious credibility ; unfortunately it's also the least of its problems .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: director jon turteltaub , who made the delightful john travolta vehicle phenomenon as well as the surprisingly above-par cool runnings decided to make this movie so shamelessly sentimental that , contrary to what this movie's promotion would have you believe , it has much more in common with patch adams than with the silence of the lambs .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it's not the kind of sentimentality that can almost bring tears to your eyes ( what dreams may come aptly demonstrated that ) but the kind that brings vomit up your esophagus ( excuse the graphic depiction ) .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it aims to " inspire " rather than to touch hearts .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: as yoda would say , inspire it does not .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it is the ultimate sign of futility when a screenwriter ( the very experienced gerald di pego ) has to resort to literally telling the audience a movie's story .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: indeed , somewhere in the beginning of instinct , one of the characters actually reads aloud the film's plot to another character .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: this , like the instance i mentioned in the first paragraph of this review , is a horrid insult to our intelligence .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: i am forced to wonder whether turteltaub and di pego did not think that we could figure out what instinct is about simply from regular conversation .
